\cf2 Video can be\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Interlaced_video"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \strokec4 interlaced}}\'a0or\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Progressive_scan"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \strokec4 progressive}}. In progressive scan systems, each refresh period updates all scan lines in each frame in sequence. When displaying a natively progressive broadcast or recorded signal, the result is optimum spatial resolution of both the stationary and moving parts of the image. Interlacing was invented as a way to reduce flicker in early\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mechanical_television"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \strokec4 mechanical}}\'a0and\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cathode_ray_tube"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \strokec4 CRT}}\'a0video displays without increasing the number of complete\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frames_per_second"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \strokec4 frames per second}}. Interlacing retains detail while requiring lower\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bandwidth_(signal_processing)"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \strokec4 bandwidth}}\'a0compared to progressive scanning.\
In interlaced video, the horizontal\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scan_line"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \strokec4 scan lines}}\'a0of each complete frame are treated as if numbered consecutively, and captured as two\'a0
\f1\i fields
