When displaying a natively interlaced signal on a progressive scan device, overall spatial resolution is degraded by simple\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Line_doubling"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \strokec4 line doubling}}\'97artifacts such as flickering or "comb" effects in moving parts of the image which appear unless special signal processing eliminates them. A procedure known as\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Deinterlacing"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \strokec4 deinterlacing}}\'a0can optimize the display of an interlaced video signal from an analog, DVD or satellite source on a progressive scan device such as an\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/LCD_television"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \strokec4 LCD television}}, digital\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Video_projector"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \strokec4 video projector}}\'a0or plasma panel. Deinterlacing cannot, however, produce\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Video_quality"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \strokec4 video quality}}\'a0that is equivalent to true progressive scan source material.\
